The Pythonicon

How to speak Python

Philosophy of code

You can think of code like an interface to enable communication between engineers and machines - code's primary function.

But some machines can't be build by a single engineer and this is the reason why companies with it's standards and regulations for easy communication exist. Basically, you want your code to be understood by other engineers as well. And because of this, you got to have a certain syntax. The syntax for writing python at IFX, in particular, is as follows...

Structure of code

Having a basic ruleset on how your code is structured, benefits the reader to understand your code.

First of all, code begins in the head, then it's projected onto a piece of paper or anything similiar. Only at the end, code is being written.
Of utmost neccesity is the modularity of your code.
Try to break the problem, you're trying to solve, into smaller pieces - 'blackboxes' for the first part. And then find a way to link these blackboxes with each other to - in the end - solve the grande probleme. For figuring out a way to link these blackboxes, it's important to know what inputs and outputs the blackbox/module is going to receive or transmit. Once the 'link' has been figured out, you can go on about solving the indivdual modules.
When designing a module, consider:

  • How could it best be integrated with the rest of the code - keep the 'link' in mind
  • Is it reasonable to structure this module as a python-class or not
  • If a python-class is the best solution: Could this class also be used on other code-projects or not
    • If yes: design the class having in mind that the inputs could differ slightly (adding multiple construction methods and making the class 'user-friendly')
    • If not: Just dont' sweat it

Keep in mind while coding:

  • Avoid using global variables as they mess with the scopes of the program.
  • Try to make your functions and methods to be as small as possible
  • Functions are meant to do ONE thing and not a bunch of stuff at the same time. E.g. if you have a function like getUsername() it should only return the username and not simultaneously wrap it into a DataFrame or anything similar
    This is probably the hardest thing to do but one should at least try to do it this way.
  • Avoid declarations of functions or methods that have a 'side-effect'. If one doesn't expect the function to do more than it's described as, it shouldn't be doing it.
  • Don't be afraid to write a few more lines of code if it is easier to comprehend than a one-liner thats cryptic.
  • Avoid declaring functions / methods that got more than three parameters.
  • Avoid try/except-blocks unless it is necessary (they make the code look messy).

When using classes for your project, make them in a seperate python file. If anybody might use this particular class, it will be easy to locate as the file's name implies its containing python class...

When writing code, I like to make it obvious, where its beginning or 'main-function' is. This can best be achieved by creating your starting point for the program at the end of the page, after all your function declarations. There is no 'main-function' in python, but there is a little trick to make something familiar:

import example_1 import example_2 ... def example_function(): ''' ... Parameters --------- Returns --------- ''' return def main(): example_function() ... if __name__ == "__main__": main() ...

Furthermore, there's a certain template for how your script should look like:

  • At the top of the script put your legal information:
    ''' © YYYY by Infineon Technologies AG. All rights reserved. Released under the terms of the GNU General Public License version 2 or later. Author(s): Your Name, ... Created on: DD.MM.YYYY Last edited: DD.MM.YYYY Version: Changes to previous version. Description: Short Description of the script. '''
  • After the legal information you import your packages, if needed:
    • import pandas as pd import datetime import numpy . . .
  • After importing your packages, define a class or declare the functions of your script:
    • def bool2int(boolean): ''' Converts boolean to integer. True, False --> 1, 0 Parameters ---------- boolean : boolean Returns --------- integer representation of input-boolean. ''' return int(boolean == True) def boolArr2int(boo_arr): ''' Converts an array of booleans to form a number representation of the array. Paramters ---------- bool_arr : arr Array of booleans to form a number. Returns ---------- bin_num : int Integer representation of boolean array ''' bin_num = 0 for d in boo_arr: bin_num = (bin_num << 1) + d return bin_num . . . Or: . . . def Example: ''' This is an example-class. ''' arr = [] def __init__(self, param_1, param_2): self.appendToArr(param_1, param_2) def _appendToArr(self, item_1, item_2): self.arr.append(item_1) self.arr.append(item_2) def setArr(self, items): ''' Sets the array of Example-Class. Paramters ---------- items : arr Replacement array. Returns ---------- None. ''' self.arr = items
  • After your functions have been defined you put your define the main-function of the script:
    • def main(): #'True' turns to '1' print(bool2int(True)) #[0, 1, 1, 0] turns to '6' print(boolArr2int([0, 1, 1, 0]))
  • Finally, you put the execution-part at the end of the file, its recommended to do it like the following:
    • if __name__ == "__main__": main()

Naming convention for variables

Most importantly: When naming a variable, its name is required to imply its purpose/function.

For the sake of uniformity, variable's names should by letter be:

  • In lower-case
  • If variable-name consists of several words: use '_' instead of grouping the words together. When naming a function or method, the opposite applies (See: Naming convention for functions and methods).
  • When defining a variable which is inteded to be used in relation to another variable, place its 'subpurpose' after its main purpose and use '_' to seperate.
    • Example: you have a dictionary which is simply called dict, when e.g. dividing this dictionary into seperate dictionaries with a subpurpose like seperating the header-information from the content of an HTML-page, the variables names should be as follows: dict_header and dict_content, respectively
  • It's recommended that often used 'purposes' - like having a temporary variable to store data inside of a loop - should be kept as short as possible: instead of temporary_variable use the common tmp. This rule applies to many 'purposes' whereby many are listed in List of abbreviated purposes
  • Variables, which ought to be used in the way a 'blackbox' works, should be indicated with a '_' preceding its name. This prevents confusion by indicating that the following is something that shouldn't or isn't meant to be understood by other engineers.

    Reasons for this might be:
    • The complexity of the purpose cannot be abstracted to be comprehensible for another engineer.
    • Its purpose is so unsignificant (See: Significance of variables/functions/methods ) that explaining it by having its name imply its functionality is impossbile. In this case it applies that anything that cannot be given a name is most likely unnecesary; another solution ought to be seeked for.
    • It's a private method or variable of a class
  • Loop counters like i, j and k are very welcome, but try to avoid the letter 'l' as a variable name - it can easily be confused. The same applies to the upper-case 'O' and similar easy-to-confuse symbols.

Naming convention for functions and methods

Most importantly: When naming a function or method, its name is required to imply its purpose/function.

E.g. having a function that converts a string to an integer: stringToInteger() ... when applying the 'abbrevation-rule' (See: Abbreviations ) the function's name would be: str2int()
When your function/method's purpose can't be abbreviated and can only be described by grouping words, the 'word-pieces' should be sperated by writing the initial letter of a word in upper-case ... E.g. getDifferenceBetweenNonNumerical()

The rationale: it serves uniformity and prevents confusion...

Comments

Comments should be avoided by following the 'golden-rule': make the code self-explanatory!

The programmer communicates by giving his modules/functions/variables/... fitting names and by adding comments, which the computer doesn't read or doesn't need to read.
Writing a comment on a hard part of the code is much appreciated, but if your code is cramped with comments it makes everything obscure.
Before writing a comment consider the following:

Am I (or would I be) confused by this part? - Yes?
Comment!

In the case you're commenting a part of your code, follow these guidelines:

  • In python you have the ability to write multi-line-comments by defining a string in the middle of nowhere - just avoid that. Unless you're writing a description for a function or you're adding legal information on the beginning of your script.
  • Instead, use real comments. When you're commenting something that doesn't fit in a single line, just put multiple comments on top of each other.
  • When E.g. commenting the purpose of a loop, put the comment before the loop, not inside or after it.
  • Don't make comments that take more time to read than the code itself.

TODOs and logging

In case you were working on a script and caught an important thought, leave a 'TODO-comment' to remember yourself and other programmers what could or should be changed or added. Who doesn't know the feeling of losing a train of thought that seemed important just because you didn't write it down anywhere. Not a pleasent feeling. If you are someone who likes to document every change - for good reasons - do it in a seperate file with a '.log' file-ending. This is not mandatory but could provide useful information for other programmers.

Annotations on functions and methods

If you want an engineer to understand your code, you have to explain it to him or her. This is especially important when you have a function or method where its name solely doesn't explain its purpose.

Primarly, you only add annotations on functions and methods that are not self-explainatory - E.g. hex2bin() needs no explanation.
Otherwise you should contemplate the function/method to require either no annotation at all or the shortest annotation possible (preventing long explanations).
For adding annotations to your functions and methods there's a simple template:

''' Description of purpose. Parameters ------- x : data-type Paramter description. y: data-type Paramter description. Returns ------- z : data-type(s) Description of return value. Explain the cases where the return value might be uncommon. '''

Abbreviations

When writing code you should try to make it as compact as possible. This can best be achieved by abbreviate certain often-occuring phrases. If you notice a repetition in your naming, try to make it as short as possible - but also comprehensible.

Here is a list of abbreviations that can be applied to most python-code:

List of abbreviated purposes

Term Abbrevation Usual purpose
temporary variable tmp to initiate a variable which's solely purpose is to temporarly store something
to 2 naming a function for converting data-types

hexadecimal hex specifying a hexadecimal number
boolean bool to initialize a variable with boolean data-type
integer int to initialize a variable with integer data-type
dictionary dict to initialize a variable with dictionary data-type
array arr to initialize a variable with array data-type
character chr/char to initialize a variable with char data-type
number num to describe a number

Significance of variables, functions and methods

Keep in mind that you can't write the perfect code - you'll always find redundancies and pieces which could have probably be made much more simple. Sometimes the urge for perfection can't be fulfilled because of either a lack of knowledge or the bond to a schedule.

So you have to decide on your own which parts of the code are really significant and where it's well invested time to drive it to perfection.


A simple rule of thumb:
If you can't explain the purpose of a code piece to your grandmother, it's probably not significant enough to abstract it to a simpler form.

Minimal computational effort

The essence of good programming is the performance of the code. So all measures must be met to make the code to be compilable as fast as possible.

Rules to write by:

  • No redundant loops
  • Only the most signifacant data should be processed
  • Avoid data-type conversions - plan ahead before initialising a variable
  • Keep it simple... Davinci once said: "Simplicity is the ultimate sophistication"


To summerize: No Schnickschnak!

Code example

Here's a little example of a program that gets a string as input and outputs all permutations of the string to the python console:

import itertools def getPermutationsOfStr(input): ''' Returns a list of permutations of the given string. Parameters ------- input : str The input-string. Returns ------- list A list of permutations of the given string. ''' return list(itertools.permutations(input)) def main(): string = input("Enter a string: ") print(getPermutationsOfStr(string)) if __name__ == "__main__": main()

For more python-examples see : group008\Allgemeines\Keusch Philip\py, altough it is recommended to look at these examples with a grain of salt as they aren't, by no means, perfect.

Reference

For the best programming conventions: Clean Code by Robert C. Martin

Epilogue

If you prefer to use your own coding-conventions you can create a dictionary or lexicon to go with your code. Altough it's recommended to stick to these conventions. Also, something really important: Even a simple python-script is a product of some sort and, as you might know, no product is fun using if there wouldn't be someone who put a little love in it. Try to understand what you and your collegues need the best and how to make it happen in a reasonable time.
